track_notes: Start by taking the LÃ´n Gwyrfai footpath on the downhill side of the station passing under the line and onto the road past Cwm Cloch Isaf. Cross the line by two level crossings. After the woods follow the path signed Rhyd Ddu off to the right. Shortly after this turn left onto the mountain track. You will cross a stile and then pass through a gate. Above about 600m the path gets more difficult with some scrambling required.

Park at the curve on B4418 or start in Rhyd Ddu (come by WHR steam train!). Pass foot of Mynydd Drws y Coed and head into Beddgelert Forest. Follow tracks to stay on the contour (more or less). Turn right onto footpath to Princess Quarry (nice tunnel). Easy to follow path rises up Moel Lefn, then Moel Yr Ogof (but where is the Ogof?) and finally Moel Hebog.
track_title: Via Moel Lefn, Moel Yr Ogof

track_notes: We paid Â£5 for all day parking near the WHR Station (toilets on platform). This was a good route with easy scrambling as described by G4TJC at around the 600m level (Thanks for info Simon). From the summit we went down to the col to the north and took a right along a waymarked route back through the forest to rejoin our original route at a blue marker post near to Beddgelert. This was an excellent walk and route on a perfect day - highly recommended.

Descend Moel-ddu following the wall, to Bwlch Cwmystradllyn near Gorseddau Quarry, SH57484484. Ascend towards Bryn Banog, quarry to your left (a bit of exposure) and Ffridd y Bwlch to your right. Either side of the wall should be Ok. From Bryn Banog cross bwlch towards Moel Hebog - sure to be boggy. Ascend South Buttress - zig-zag path found for some of the way.

This is hard work. It took me 2hr 45m in ascent, but including a 25-min lunch break.

track_notes:
Park near barns, Cwrt Isaf, SH540464. Beware rough approach track. Honesty box but no set fee displayed.

Track starts over stile to right of barn. Several more follow but then the path deteriorates to sheep tracks and the odd bit of quad track. Keep left of Afon Cwm llefrith. Hebog mine (copper) can be viewed to the other side of the stream.

Cross final stile at Bwlch Meillionen and head right for final ~250m of ascent.
